{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_f0a1d4aa55d64415bf02a43b","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t<h1 align=\"center\">\n2\t<img alt=\"logo\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/logo.png\">\n3\t</h1>\n4\t\n5\t<div align=\"center\">\n6\t<img alt=\"license\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-lightgrey\">\n7\t<img alt=\"test\" src=\"https://github.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/workflows/Test/badge.svg\">\n8\t<img alt=\"codecov\" src=\"https://codecov.io/gh/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=QqIqDQ7FZi\">\n9\t<a href=\"https://pepy.tech/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"downloads\" src=\"https://pepy.tech/badge/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n10\t<a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"pypi\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n11\t</div>\n12\t\n13\t## Introduction\n14\t\n15\t`fastapi-pagination` is a Python library designed to simplify pagination in FastAPI applications. \n16\tIt provides a set of utility functions and data models to help you paginate your database queries \n17\tand return paginated responses to your clients.\n18\t\n19\tWith `fastapi-pagination`, you can easily define pagination parameters in your FastAPI endpoint functions,\n20\tand use them to generate paginated responses that include the requested subset of your data.\n21\tThe library supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination.\n22\t\n23\t`fastapi-pagination` is built on top of the popular `fastapi` library, and it works with a wide range \n24\tof SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks. It also supports async/await syntax and is compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n25\t\n26\tFeatures:\n27\t\n28\t* Simplifies pagination in FastAPI applications.\n29\t* Supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination\n30\t* Works with a wide range of SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks, including `SQLAlchemy`, `Tortoise ORM`, and `PyMongo`.\n31\t* Supports async/await syntax.\n32\t* Compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n33\t\n34\t----\n35\t\n36\tFor more information on how to use fastapi-pagination, please refer to the \n37\t[official documentation](https://uriyyo-fastapi-pagination.netlify.app/).\n38\t\n39\t---\n40\t\n41\t## Installation\n42\t\n43\t```bash\n44\tpip install fastapi-pagination\n45\t```\n46\t\n47\t## Quickstart\n48\t\n49\tAll you need to do is to use `Page` class as a return type for your endpoint and call `paginate` function\n50\ton data you want to paginate.\n51\t\n52\t```py\n53\tfrom fastapi import FastAPI\n54\tfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n55\t\n56\t# import all you need from fastapi-pagination\n57\tfrom fastapi_pagination import Page, add_pagination, paginate\n58\t\n59\tapp = FastAPI()  # create FastAPI app\n60\tadd_pagination(app)  # important! add pagination to your app\n61\t\n62\t\n63\tclass UserOut(BaseModel):  # define your model\n64\t    name: str = Field(..., example=\"Steve\")\n65\t    surname: str = Field(..., example=\"Rogers\")\n66\t\n67\t\n68\tusers = [  # create some data\n69\t    UserOut(name=\"Steve\", surname=\"Rogers\"),\n70\t    # ...\n71\t]\n72\t\n73\t\n74\t# req: GET /users\n75\t@app.get(\"/users\")\n76\tasync def get_users() -> Page[UserOut]:\n77\t    # use Page[UserOut] as return type annotation\n78\t    return paginate(users)  # use paginate function to paginate your data\n79\t```\n80\t\n81\tPlease, be careful when you work with databases, because default `paginate` will require to load all data in memory.\n82\t\n83\tFor instance, if you use `SQLAlchemy` you can use `paginate` from `fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy` module.\n84\t\n85\t```python\n86\tfrom sqlalchemy import select\n87\tfrom fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy import paginate\n88\t\n89\t\n90\t@app.get(\"/users\")\n91\tdef get_users(db: Session = Depends(get_db)) -> Page[UserOut]:\n92\t    return paginate(db, select(User).order_by(User.created_at))\n93\t```\n94\t\n95\t---\n96\t\n97\tCode from `Quickstart` will generate OpenAPI schema as bellow:\n98\t\n99\t<div align=\"center\">\n100\t<img alt=\"app-example\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/example.png\">\n101\t</div>\n102\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"990f92e9-3855-44a9-8be0-d8dcf3b4b201","uuid":"9f57e04f-98b1-4074-a410-bc4debd81ccf","timestamp":"2026-04-06T23:22:26.305Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"<h1 align=\"center\">\n<img alt=\"logo\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/logo.png\">\n</h1>\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n<img alt=\"license\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-lightgrey\">\n<img alt=\"test\" src=\"https://github.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/workflows/Test/badge.svg\">\n<img alt=\"codecov\" src=\"https://codecov.io/gh/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=QqIqDQ7FZi\">\n<a href=\"https://pepy.tech/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"downloads\" src=\"https://pepy.tech/badge/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n<a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/fastapi-pagination\"><img alt=\"pypi\" src=\"https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/fastapi-pagination\"></a>\n</div>\n\n## Introduction\n\n`fastapi-pagination` is a Python library designed to simplify pagination in FastAPI applications. \nIt provides a set of utility functions and data models to help you paginate your database queries \nand return paginated responses to your clients.\n\nWith `fastapi-pagination`, you can easily define pagination parameters in your FastAPI endpoint functions,\nand use them to generate paginated responses that include the requested subset of your data.\nThe library supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination.\n\n`fastapi-pagination` is built on top of the popular `fastapi` library, and it works with a wide range \nof SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks. It also supports async/await syntax and is compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n\nFeatures:\n\n* Simplifies pagination in FastAPI applications.\n* Supports a variety of pagination strategies, including cursor-based pagination and page-based pagination\n* Works with a wide range of SQL and NoSQL databases frameworks, including `SQLAlchemy`, `Tortoise ORM`, and `PyMongo`.\n* Supports async/await syntax.\n* Compatible with Python 3.10 and higher.\n\n----\n\nFor more information on how to use fastapi-pagination, please refer to the \n[official documentation](https://uriyyo-fastapi-pagination.netlify.app/).\n\n---\n\n## Installation\n\n```bash\npip install fastapi-pagination\n```\n\n## Quickstart\n\nAll you need to do is to use `Page` class as a return type for your endpoint and call `paginate` function\non data you want to paginate.\n\n```py\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n\n# import all you need from fastapi-pagination\nfrom fastapi_pagination import Page, add_pagination, paginate\n\napp = FastAPI()  # create FastAPI app\nadd_pagination(app)  # important! add pagination to your app\n\n\nclass UserOut(BaseModel):  # define your model\n    name: str = Field(..., example=\"Steve\")\n    surname: str = Field(..., example=\"Rogers\")\n\n\nusers = [  # create some data\n    UserOut(name=\"Steve\", surname=\"Rogers\"),\n    # ...\n]\n\n\n# req: GET /users\n@app.get(\"/users\")\nasync def get_users() -> Page[UserOut]:\n    # use Page[UserOut] as return type annotation\n    return paginate(users)  # use paginate function to paginate your data\n```\n\nPlease, be careful when you work with databases, because default `paginate` will require to load all data in memory.\n\nFor instance, if you use `SQLAlchemy` you can use `paginate` from `fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy` module.\n\n```python\nfrom sqlalchemy import select\nfrom fastapi_pagination.ext.sqlalchemy import paginate\n\n\n@app.get(\"/users\")\ndef get_users(db: Session = Depends(get_db)) -> Page[UserOut]:\n    return paginate(db, select(User).order_by(User.created_at))\n```\n\n---\n\nCode from `Quickstart` will generate OpenAPI schema as bellow:\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n<img alt=\"app-example\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/uriyyo/fastapi-pagination/main/docs/img/example.png\">\n</div>\n","numLines":102,"startLine":1,"totalLines":102}}}
